    "Then, for every ϵ, ε > 0 the ε-covering number N (ε, F) of F satisfies P N (ε, F) ≤ (2R + 2R 0) cT +1 /ε q ≥ P(B ϵ) ≥ 1 -ϵ(18)where c = c 2, R = M ν 2r log(2W/ϵ) and R 0 = ∥θ pre ∥ ∞ as in Lemma 9.",
    "Moreover, when the loss function ℓ is 1-Lipschitz, composing F with Λ in Lemma 7 yieldsP N (ε, Λ(F)) ≤ (2R + 2R 0) cT +1 /ε q ≥ P(B ϵ) ≥ 1 -ϵ(19)Proof.",
    "This is a direct consequence of Lemmata Lemmata 4 and 6: with probability at least 1 -ϵ, we haveN (ε, F) ≤ R • 2 -⌊log 2 (ε/L θpre LoRA)⌋ q ≤ 2R • L θpre LoRA /ε q ≤ 2R • (2R + 2R 0) cT /ε q ≤ (2R + 2R 0) cT +1 /ε q. B.2.3 Step 3 -Generalization Bounds Conditioned on Covering Number BoundsNext, we control the randomized generalization gap G, as defined in (3), conditioned on the event B ϵ, as defined in ( 16).",
    "Upon conditioning on the right realizations, which happen with high probability, our covering number bounds give us access to the Dudley's integral estimate; see e.g.",
    "[van der Vaart and Wellner, 1996, Corollary 2.2.8].Lemma 9 (Conditional Generalization Bounds for \"Derandomized\" LoRAs)."
